Messi will turn 27 the day before Argentina play Nigeria in their last group game.

Given that they are in an apparently less demanding section, he and his team-mates will presumably be in the mood to celebrate after that match.

How far they progress beyond that will depend not only on Sabella sorting out his tactics but whether they can bring their collective ego down to earth.

They should have been punished by the Bosnians in a ragged, disorganised first half, although they did improve when Sabella sent on a couple of decent substitutes and reverted to an orthodox back four.

Yet even in the closing stages, after Messi had put them two up, that old arrogance returned and they conceded one goal and almost threw the win away.

